Of course, there's
Accessible Twitter Feeds.

00:11:54.000 --> 00:11:56.320
This is also a lot of stuff
that's also in the handbook as

00:11:56.320 --> 00:11:58.480
well, so if you wanna know
some good starting points,

00:11:58.480 --> 00:11:58.960
here it is.

00:11:59.840 --> 00:12:02.240
Video players, there's
also Able Player as a plugin.

00:12:02.240 --> 00:12:05.600
Able Player's a really nice
one that really gives a lot of

00:12:05.600 --> 00:12:07.680
options for different
kinds of disabilities.

00:12:08.720 --> 00:12:10.640
Now, of course, you have to
make sure your content is also

00:12:10.640 --> 00:12:11.520
available that way.

00:12:15.440 --> 00:12:19.520
So I didn't list a lot of
options here and I've so far

00:12:19.520 --> 00:12:22.400
kind of pointed out
everything has some problems.

00:12:23.280 --> 00:12:26.240
So, really, that's why it's
all on us as developers,

00:12:26.240 --> 00:12:28.400
site owners, site managers,

00:12:28.400 --> 00:12:31.280
it's on us to make sure we do
our due diligence.

00:12:31.280 --> 00:12:33.440
We can't wait until QC comes in.

00:12:33.440 --> 00:12:38.720
We can't wait until the end
user has to complain or try and

00:12:38.720 --> 00:12:39.680
access the content.

00:12:40.640 --> 00:12:46.160
So we've got nice cartography
tools on a workbench going over

00:12:46.160 --> 00:12:48.800
maps, and really, we're gonna
use those cartography tools.

00:12:48.800 --> 00:12:50.880
Just the tools for ourselves,

00:12:50.880 --> 00:12:53.920
so how are we going
to test our sites?

00:12:55.200 --> 00:12:56.880
So test, test, test, and vet.

00:12:58.080 --> 00:13:01.840
Now you might be thinking, "I
don't know how to test or vet."

00:13:02.960 --> 00:13:05.680
Well, at the very least,
you can still do your part

00:13:05.680 --> 00:13:07.200
and look into the history.

00:13:07.760 --> 00:13:10.000
Okay, what--let's
go into the GitHub.

00:13:10.000 --> 00:13:13.680
As devs, we probably don't feel
too concerned of just jumping in

00:13:13.680 --> 00:13:15.280
and looking at
the issue trackers.

00:13:17.280 --> 00:13:18.960
They've been kind
of showed here, right?

00:13:18.960 --> 00:13:21.840
We have Elementors.

00:13:22.960 --> 00:13:25.200
Making no dig at
them but there's,

00:13:25.200 --> 00:13:27.040
you know, still 21
issues still open.

00:13:27.920 --> 00:13:31.760
Still issues with maybe
some keyboard accessibility.

00:13:31.760 --> 00:13:34.000
Now, there's 64
closed, which is great.

00:13:34.000 --> 00:13:37.120
Now, for some
plugins, some tools,

00:13:37.120 --> 00:13:39.520
that might not get enough
traction to have a lot of people

00:13:39.520 --> 00:13:43.040
diving into the accessibility,
so it's also important to check

00:13:43.040 --> 00:13:44.480
is there even any
statement at all?

00:13:44.480 --> 00:13:47.760
So if it's silence
about accessibility,

00:13:47.760 --> 00:13:50.480
that's probably a bad sign
that they probably

00:13:50.480 --> 00:13:51.280
aren't thinking about it.

00:13:52.880 --> 00:13:56.320
So, you know,
even Beaver Builder,

00:13:56.320 --> 00:13:58.160
for example, has
statements about it,

00:13:59.200 --> 00:14:01.840
trying to work
towards it, right?

00:14:05.280 --> 00:14:07.200
And then, of course,
search for reviews.

00:14:07.200 --> 00:14:09.120
Maybe you're
still kind of unsure,

00:14:09.120 --> 00:14:10.880
there's a lot of specialists,
there's a lot of people,

00:14:10.880 --> 00:14:12.880
I mean, all the
presenters today,

00:14:12.880 --> 00:14:15.520
I mean, there's plenty of people
that are trying to help educate

00:14:15.520 --> 00:14:20.080
and grow knowledge on
maybe some pain points

00:14:20.080 --> 00:14:21.200
or in some growth areas.

00:14:22.320 --> 00:14:26.720
Well, you know, you even have--
oh, I think I shared that one.

00:14:28.720 --> 00:14:31.040
But you have, like,
a bright clear web.

00:14:31.600 --> 00:14:34.560
You've got multiple--
that are actually testing out,

00:14:34.560 --> 00:14:36.480
sometimes even end
users are saying,

00:14:36.480 --> 00:14:37.840
"Hey, I can't
actually use this."

00:14:38.720 --> 00:14:42.640
But at the end of the day, it's
about actually, really, testing

00:14:42.640 --> 00:14:45.840
the demos, testing the
code, testing it on a sandbox,

00:14:45.840 --> 00:14:46.720
testing it yourself.

00:14:48.560 --> 00:14:51.440
You know, even Graham earlier,
watching all these streams,

00:14:51.440 --> 00:14:53.840
says, "You know, you
need to know how to tab,

00:14:54.480 --> 00:14:55.360
use a keyboard.

00:14:55.920 --> 00:14:57.840
Don't just assume
it's a mouse."

00:15:00.160 --> 00:15:02.000
So we need to test, right?

00:15:02.000 --> 00:15:03.920
We need to test with
different kinds of tools.

00:15:03.920 --> 00:15:06.080
So a lot of people go
to automated tools, right?

00:15:06.800 --> 00:15:10.000
So we've got Tota11y,
Wave, aXe, ARC Toolkit.

00:15:10.000 --> 00:15:13.120
These are extensions you can
install into your browser to be

00:15:13.120 --> 00:15:15.200
able to say, "Okay,
well, quick assessment."

00:15:16.800 --> 00:15:18.320
Then you've got Pa11y.

00:15:18.880 --> 00:15:21.520
That's if you wanna create
dashboards for yourself and do

00:15:21.520 --> 00:15:23.120
it through--against
the A11y build tools.

00:15:24.560 --> 00:15:26.880
Then you've got
Tenon.io, Siteimprove,

00:15:26.880 --> 00:15:29.120
these types of--hey, they've
already created a dashboard,

00:15:29.120 --> 00:15:30.800
they've already
created a system,

00:15:30.800 --> 00:15:32.960
that's crawling your site and
looking through everything.

00:15:33.520 --> 00:15:36.400
And there's plenty more
tools available and out there.

00:15:38.800 --> 00:15:40.240
But these are all
great starting points.

00:15:40.960 --> 00:15:43.040
Now, everyone's throwing
out different amounts,

00:15:43.600 --> 00:15:46.960
but in general, automated
tools can only catch so much,

00:15:46.960 --> 00:15:51.440
maybe 25% to 50% of
even the--text space.

00:15:54.640 --> 00:15:59.040
So really, manual
testing is key because

00:16:00.720 --> 00:16:03.280
how would you know if a
multi-step checkout process with

00:16:03.280 --> 00:16:06.480
multiple tabs, with
an automated tool,

00:16:06.480 --> 00:16:08.240
needs to fill out
all the form fields,

00:16:08.240 --> 00:16:10.240
fill it out, some
of them incorrectly,

00:16:10.240 --> 00:16:12.320
hit submit, find
where the errors are,

00:16:12.320 --> 00:16:13.840
and make sure that
they're properly tied?

00:16:14.480 --> 00:16:18.240
That's not that easy to achieve
without a lot of customization

00:16:18.240 --> 00:16:19.440
with automated tools.

00:16:20.480 --> 00:16:22.800
Same thing, is there an
automated tool to run through to

00:16:22.800 --> 00:16:25.280
confirm all your captions
are well set up inside

00:16:25.280 --> 00:16:26.240
of your videos?

00:16:26.240 --> 00:16:27.840
No, it takes humans.

00:16:27.840 --> 00:16:30.800
That's why we even have
humans writing closed captions.

00:16:34.800 --> 00:16:39.520
So I think one of the main
things that I find with devs,

00:16:39.520 --> 00:16:41.200
you know, why there
are so many gaps?

00:16:41.200 --> 00:16:43.520
Why do I see ARIA hidden on a
whole bunch of things that need

00:16:43.520 --> 00:16:44.000
to be read?

00:16:44.000 --> 00:16:46.960
Why are there these mistakes
that are coming through?

00:16:48.000 --> 00:16:51.200
And it's because as humans we
have a hard time stepping

00:16:51.200 --> 00:16:52.080
out of our own shoes.

00:16:52.080 --> 00:16:54.640
We're used to our
normal, everyday life.

00:16:54.640 --> 00:17:00.000
Some people are, you know, have
sight and do cater everything to

00:17:00.000 --> 00:17:04.640
site users and so, really, it's
about picking up these tools.

00:17:06.000 --> 00:17:07.440
The ones that I've
kind of listed here,

00:17:07.440 --> 00:17:10.240
NVDA, LipSurf,
VoiceOver, TalkBack,

00:17:10.880 --> 00:17:14.240
all of them are actually,
to a degree, free to use.

00:17:14.800 --> 00:17:18.160
NVDA, of course,
would love donations,

00:17:18.160 --> 00:17:20.400
but--so if you're on Windows
and you need a screen reader,

00:17:20.960 --> 00:17:21.840
install it.

00:17:21.840 --> 00:17:24.720
Don't be afraid to just close
your eyes and try and experience

00:17:24.720 --> 00:17:28.320
what it's like going through
your website or just regular

00:17:28.320 --> 00:17:31.840
websites and you'll see the
extreme pain points that many

00:17:31.840 --> 00:17:32.720
sites provide.

00:17:34.080 --> 00:17:38.240
I mentioned LipSurf,
so Dragon is another,

00:17:38.240 --> 00:17:40.880
you know, voice
dictation software.

00:17:41.440 --> 00:17:45.120
Generally hasn't been that
great for web traversal,

00:17:45.120 --> 00:17:47.520
and so LipSurf is kind of
another alternative

00:17:47.520 --> 00:17:48.160
that's also free.

00:17:48.160 --> 00:17:50.640
It's an extension that's
available for Chrome that also

00:17:50.640 --> 00:17:53.120
has some commands to be
able to reverse everything.

00:17:54.000 --> 00:17:57.680
If you have a mobile
device, and pretty much almost,

00:17:57.680 --> 00:17:59.840
I think, everyone
to a degree has,

00:18:01.200 --> 00:18:03.920
now you can use
VoiceOver, Voice Control,

00:18:03.920 --> 00:18:06.320
through MacOS and iOS.

00:18:06.320 --> 00:18:09.200
You've got TalkBack and
Voice Access on Android for the

00:18:09.200 --> 00:18:13.360
accessibility sweep, so they're
already built in so you already

00:18:13.360 --> 00:18:14.160
have options.

00:18:14.720 --> 00:18:17.120
So go into your
settings, turn 'em on,

00:18:17.120 --> 00:18:18.640
see what that
experience is like.

00:18:19.280 --> 00:18:23.120
'Cause not everyone's going to
be--your end users are not going

00:18:23.120 --> 00:18:25.600
to be pro-screen-reader users.

00:18:25.600 --> 00:18:27.840
It's gonna be people
that just, "I needed to,

00:18:27.840 --> 00:18:29.280
you know, get through the day."

00:18:30.080 --> 00:18:34.960
So I think that's one of the
key things is if I were to say,

00:18:34.960 --> 00:18:37.440
stress anything
about today or anything,

00:18:37.440 --> 00:18:41.120
is pick up one of these software
tools and there's other assisted

00:18:41.120 --> 00:18:44.320
technology, of course,
as well, and try it out.

00:18:44.320 --> 00:18:46.240
And that will kind of show
you the pain points

00:18:47.040 --> 00:18:48.160
of what you're building.

00:18:50.560 --> 00:18:51.920
So, 'cause what
I'm getting at is,

00:18:51.920 --> 00:18:55.520
you know, as you saw, there's
many plugins that--and page

00:18:55.520 --> 00:18:56.640
tools that all have issues.

00:18:56.640 --> 00:19:00.400
There's even ones that are
promoting accessibility that

00:19:00.400 --> 00:19:01.200
have problems.

00:19:01.840 --> 00:19:04.640
So us as developers,
as site owners,

00:19:04.640 --> 00:19:08.400
as site managers, we're
gonna need to patch things.

00:19:08.400 --> 00:19:09.840
We're gonna need to fix things.

00:19:11.520 --> 00:19:14.400
So you're--and you know,
you've got here a nice kind of

00:19:14.400 --> 00:19:16.000
beaten-up road with potholes

00:19:16.000 --> 00:19:17.600
and definitely needs
a paving, right?

00:19:18.880 --> 00:19:21.200
So, DIY repairs are needed.

00:19:21.200 --> 00:19:23.840
So let's actually go
into some of these, right?

00:19:23.840 --> 00:19:27.200
Well, what could we do to
improve this experience?

00:19:28.400 --> 00:19:30.080
So this is where we're
gonna get more devi side.

00:19:32.720 --> 00:19:37.520
So, situations that I feel I
often see in reviewing people's

00:19:37.520 --> 00:19:40.400
code and everything, is
that are missed.

00:19:40.400 --> 00:19:42.800
So we've got
sticky headers, right?

00:19:42.800 --> 00:19:44.240
Everyone loves sticky headers.

00:19:44.960 --> 00:19:46.880
It's still kind of a
focused interface,

00:19:46.880 --> 00:19:49.600
really, for sighted
mouse users or touch users.

00:19:50.720 --> 00:19:53.520
But it's not that
it's a bad practice, per se.

00:19:54.560 --> 00:19:56.560
The problem is, is
that there are people

00:19:56.560 --> 00:19:58.080
and we are getting older, right?

00:19:58.080 --> 00:20:02.320
And eyesight, unfortunately,
doesn't really last forever.

00:20:03.440 --> 00:20:10.080
And so, people need to zoom,
increase the screen size so that

00:20:10.080 --> 00:20:11.920
they can actually--or
magnify it so they can

00:20:11.920 --> 00:20:13.040
actually read content.

00:20:14.800 --> 00:20:16.720
So let's take a look
at an example, right?

00:20:19.200 --> 00:20:22.320
So, let's actually
change our zoom.

00:20:22.320 --> 00:20:27.120
So we're at 100%, and
let's get out to 200%,

00:20:28.720 --> 00:20:30.320
and let's get up to 400%.

00:20:32.720 --> 00:20:38.400
And what is this experience for
someone that needs to zoom in

00:20:38.400 --> 00:20:39.280
order to read content?

00:20:39.280 --> 00:20:40.960
Now, again, this is
with Navigation Open,

00:20:41.760 --> 00:20:45.840
but the amount of space
on a 1280 by 1024 screen,

00:20:45.840 --> 00:20:50.240
this is what's simulating
here, when you zoom in at 400%,

00:20:51.360 --> 00:20:53.360
that's really not
ending up that tall.

00:20:53.360 --> 00:20:55.120
You don't really have
enough real estate space.

00:20:55.120 --> 00:20:58.160
It's actually
shorter than most phones.

00:20:59.600 --> 00:21:02.400
So sticky here, where it's
following you around and then

00:21:02.400 --> 00:21:03.920
you have navigation
and that's open,

00:21:04.800 --> 00:21:10.400
how easily can I
read--"Contact," okay.

00:21:10.400 --> 00:21:13.360
The experience is tough
'cause now we have also a sticky

00:21:13.360 --> 00:21:14.720
"Pricing" area.

00:21:15.680 --> 00:21:18.480
And again, this is not
to--I see this on many,

00:21:18.480 --> 00:21:20.880
many sites, so this is not
just something with Divi.

00:21:24.160 --> 00:21:25.600
So how do we counter that?

00:21:25.600 --> 00:21:28.880
So you can actually use
media queries with min heights.

00:21:28.880 --> 00:21:30.720
Many people are aware
of min widths, right?

00:21:31.360 --> 00:21:32.880
But you can
actually do min heights.

00:21:32.880 --> 00:21:35.440
So you can do something
along the lines of min

00:21:35.440 --> 00:21:37.840
height is 30 EM, right?

00:21:37.840 --> 00:21:42.960
So ems versus pixels to account
for a little bit with different

00:21:42.960 --> 00:21:45.280
font choices and font sizes
people might use

00:21:45.280 --> 00:21:46.080
within their browser.

00:21:47.120 --> 00:21:49.360
And so, maybe if
you're tall enough,

00:21:49.360 --> 00:21:52.080
then let's have a
sticky, and otherwise,

00:21:52.080 --> 00:21:53.360
just have it be normal.

00:21:55.200 --> 00:21:58.720
Modal dialogs, it's
very, very, very,

00:21:58.720 --> 00:22:00.880
very common to do it wrong

00:22:00.880 --> 00:22:02.720
'cause it is very
easy to do it wrong.

00:22:03.680 --> 00:22:05.840
It requires a lot
about focus management,

00:22:06.400 --> 00:22:09.440
being able to say, "As soon as I
toggle something I need to move

00:22:09.440 --> 00:22:12.640
into that area, then I need to
be contained within that area,"

00:22:13.280 --> 00:22:16.400
because the idea of a modal
dialog is that you need to

00:22:16.400 --> 00:22:18.960
complete this task before
you move on to something else.

00:22:18.960 --> 00:22:21.200
That's why you
often have, you know,

00:22:21.200 --> 00:22:26.320
the grayed-out areas of a page.

00:22:26.320 --> 00:22:29.600
But okay, let's--try me.

00:22:29.600 --> 00:22:32.160
Okay, something
popped up on the screen.

00:22:32.800 --> 00:22:35.120
Are you under 18?
Okay, this is just a demo.

00:22:36.640 --> 00:22:42.400
And so I'll tab through and you
can see that at least we know

00:22:43.040 --> 00:22:47.600
that tabbing through this, the
content is actually--

00:22:48.560 --> 00:22:51.200
the user's focus is
nowhere inside this area.

00:22:53.120 --> 00:22:55.840
So, as a screen reader user,
they may never even know that

00:22:55.840 --> 00:22:56.880
something even popped up.

00:22:56.880 --> 00:22:59.440
As a keyboard user, how do I
even get to this information?

00:23:00.400 --> 00:23:02.880
So then, okay, well, I need to
move focus inside and then I

00:23:02.880 --> 00:23:05.920
need to be contained within
side because a screen reader

00:23:05.920 --> 00:23:08.880
user might not know that they've
left a dialog and now they've

00:23:08.880 --> 00:23:11.440
ended up in--there's hot keys
to jump all over the page.

00:23:12.160 --> 00:23:14.800
And so if they're outside of it,
they don't know how to complete

00:23:14.800 --> 00:23:16.720
the task before coming back in.

00:23:18.320 --> 00:23:20.080
And then, of course,
when you escape it,

00:23:20.080 --> 00:23:21.840
it shifts that focus
back to where you were.

00:23:24.800 --> 00:23:28.240
So, some promising aspects
is there's a new attribute,

00:23:28.240 --> 00:23:32.080
a newer attribute, inert,
which doesn't have

00:23:32.080 --> 00:23:33.200
perfect support yet.

00:23:33.840 --> 00:23:35.840
So if you mix that with
aria-hidden equals true and you

00:23:35.840 --> 00:23:39.600
apply that to pretty much
everything behind your content

00:23:39.600 --> 00:23:43.120
modal, that pretty much
contains everyone inside,

00:23:43.760 --> 00:23:45.040
because screen
reader users have,

00:23:45.040 --> 00:23:46.960
really, no other content
to really interact with.

00:23:46.960 --> 00:23:48.080
Same thing with keyboards.

00:23:49.520 --> 00:23:52.160
And something of note
in Safari for VoiceOver,

00:23:52.160 --> 00:23:56.160
there's bugs across all of
these operating systems

00:23:56.160 --> 00:23:57.680
and browsers, right?

00:23:58.400 --> 00:24:00.800
So they actually have an issue
where focus doesn't actually

00:24:00.800 --> 00:24:04.960
move inside if you actually
have--the modal display none and

00:24:04.960 --> 00:24:05.680
then you show it.

00:24:06.240 --> 00:24:07.920
If it just pops in,
that's a little bit different,

00:24:07.920 --> 00:24:10.560
so use visibility hidden if
you were to actually hide this.

00:24:12.640 --> 00:24:14.720
And something, you know, I'm
talking about Safari as well,

00:24:15.520 --> 00:24:19.360
in iOS, is that
actually accessible names,

00:24:19.360 --> 00:24:20.960
you should have had an
accessible name to your button

00:24:20.960 --> 00:24:23.840
in the first place, but I see so
many times hamburger menus that

00:24:23.840 --> 00:24:26.320
pretty much have no name
and just visuals, right?

00:24:26.320 --> 00:24:27.040
The three bars.

00:24:28.560 --> 00:24:37.760
And those pretty much are always
skipped by VoiceOver because

00:24:37.760 --> 00:24:39.360
they would never
even know exist.

00:24:39.360 --> 00:24:40.640
You try and flick,
you try and tab,

00:24:40.640 --> 00:24:43.600
anything and
nothing really happens.

00:24:43.600 --> 00:24:45.280
There's no way of
interacting with it.

00:24:45.280 --> 00:24:48.000
Now, there's plenty of other
issues but at least the screen

00:24:48.000 --> 00:24:49.840
readers and desktop
might actually land on it,

00:24:49.840 --> 00:24:52.080
at least let you know that's
clickable or if it's a link,

00:24:52.080 --> 00:24:53.920
they might actually just
at least read the URL.

00:24:58.000 --> 00:25:00.560
So what are some more
situations often missed?

00:25:01.280 --> 00:25:03.840
So we've got what I
call "div-itis."

00:25:04.480 --> 00:25:07.520
Concerns for, you know,
anything interactive,

00:25:07.520 --> 00:25:10.080
you see it all the time:
pagination for carousels,

00:25:10.080 --> 00:25:12.720
you see buttons that
look like a button

00:25:12.720 --> 00:25:14.320
but, really, it's just a div.

00:25:14.320 --> 00:25:15.920
And I see developers
all the time that go,

00:25:15.920 --> 00:25:19.200
"Okay, well, I'll throw in a div
and then I'm gonna put a--okay,

00:25:19.920 --> 00:25:23.120
well," screen readers don't
know it's a button, a--button.

00:25:23.760 --> 00:25:25.840
All right, the keyboard users
can't access it 'cause there's

00:25:25.840 --> 00:25:27.280
no tab index set.

00:25:27.280 --> 00:25:28.720
Okay, tab index equals zero.

00:25:29.680 --> 00:25:31.920
And then, on top
of that, they go,

00:25:31.920 --> 00:25:33.600
"Okay, well, that should
fix everything because

00:25:33.600 --> 00:25:34.480
I have a click binding."

00:25:35.520 --> 00:25:37.840
But the click binding doesn't
get called because the keyboards

00:25:37.840 --> 00:25:39.680
aren't tied to it anymore.

00:25:40.400 --> 00:25:43.360
So now you have to
add in on enter,

00:25:43.360 --> 00:25:46.080
on space bar, to actually
trigger your click events.

00:25:46.720 --> 00:25:48.720
Or is that even really worth it?

00:25:48.720 --> 00:25:51.440
You could have just created
button type equals button.

00:25:52.480 --> 00:25:54.320
The same concerns
happen with anchors

00:25:54.320 --> 00:25:56.000
with no H reference.

00:25:56.000 --> 00:25:57.600
They end up being
kind of just like a div.

00:25:58.400 --> 00:25:59.680
So, same concerns happen.

00:25:59.680 --> 00:26:01.520
So, as developers,
as site owners,

00:26:01.520 --> 00:26:03.360
if you're creating
a button or, sorry,

00:26:03.360 --> 00:26:05.920
a link, and you
have no real H reference,

00:26:05.920 --> 00:26:08.880
you're gonna like, "I don't
know where that would point to,"

00:26:08.880 --> 00:26:10.880
you're probably wanting to
create an actual button.

00:26:11.680 --> 00:26:14.640
And I do note type
equals button because,

00:26:15.360 --> 00:26:18.480
it's a little thing
but forms actually,

00:26:20.240 --> 00:26:21.920
if you hit "enter"
inside of an input field,

00:26:22.720 --> 00:26:26.240
will actually trigger
the first submit option,

00:26:26.240 --> 00:26:28.720
and that submit, the default
state of a button

00:26:28.720 --> 00:26:30.720
is type equals submit.

00:26:30.720 --> 00:26:32.160
So it'll actually trigger that.

00:26:32.160 --> 00:26:34.320
So that's why most of the
buttons that I see if they're

00:26:34.320 --> 00:26:37.760
toggle open, do something, type
equals button is something you'd

00:26:37.760 --> 00:26:38.640
wanna throw on there.

00:26:40.400 --> 00:26:45.920
And then carousels,
slideshows, I see all the time,

00:26:45.920 --> 00:26:47.520
you know, it's
automatic rotation,

00:26:48.240 --> 00:26:51.440
rotating through items and
there's even tools where it's,

00:26:51.440 --> 00:26:53.600
"Okay, well," and you set focus.

00:26:53.600 --> 00:26:56.400
When you set focus, pause
it, or when you hover

00:26:56.400 --> 00:26:57.200
over it, pause it.

00:26:58.320 --> 00:27:00.480
And yeah, for
digesting content, great.

00:27:01.280 --> 00:27:04.880
But about someone with maybe
ADHD or someone that has--gets

00:27:04.880 --> 00:27:08.720
sick from motion, they have no
way of turning it off or I guess

00:27:08.720 --> 00:27:11.440
they just have to stare down a
carousel for the rest of the

00:27:11.440 --> 00:27:13.040
time of being on that page.

00:27:13.040 --> 00:27:14.960
And that's not
really enjoyable at all.

00:27:16.240 --> 00:27:20.320
So a pause button is absolutely
necessary in order for it to be

00:27:20.880 --> 00:27:21.760
really accessible.

00:27:22.480 --> 00:27:24.560
Or really, don't even
have automatic rotation.

00:27:24.560 --> 00:27:25.040
That would be great.

00:27:28.320 --> 00:27:31.200
So I'll also get into some
maybe aria overlooked items.

00:27:31.200 --> 00:27:35.120
Aria-expanded is really the base
of any toggle when you wanna

00:27:35.120 --> 00:27:39.360
open and close it
because--so the screen reader,

00:27:39.360 --> 00:27:41.760
to kind of give you an idea of
what that experience is like,

00:27:41.760 --> 00:27:44.720
so sighted users, sites
cater to you all the time.

00:27:45.520 --> 00:27:48.800
Let's say I click on a features
or hover over a feature,

00:27:49.600 --> 00:27:51.920
and it shows something, right?

00:27:51.920 --> 00:27:56.880
Sites have been designed to
account for sighted users for a

00:27:56.880 --> 00:27:57.600
long, long time.

00:27:58.640 --> 00:28:02.560
So I get immediate
feedback provided to me that,

00:28:02.560 --> 00:28:05.600
oh okay, for editor, design, all
these things have been shown.

00:28:07.760 --> 00:28:11.520
But as a screen reader
user, none of that's actually

00:28:11.520 --> 00:28:14.240
happening for you
because the software itself,

00:28:14.240 --> 00:28:15.600
think of it as a pinhole view.

00:28:15.600 --> 00:28:18.000
You're only seeing a
little--one piece at a time.

00:28:19.760 --> 00:28:22.000
So when you're on a
button, when you're on an area,

00:28:22.640 --> 00:28:25.040
all that's being
announced is just that area.

00:28:25.600 --> 00:28:30.320
Now, there are tools
within aria to help with that,

00:28:30.320 --> 00:28:33.840
so Focus Management
helps, ARIA Live helps,

00:28:33.840 --> 00:28:36.400
and some of these
attributes like aria-expanded.

00:28:36.400 --> 00:28:39.040
And what will happen is, when
you first land on that button

00:28:39.040 --> 00:28:40.240
and you, you know, click.

00:28:41.360 --> 00:28:44.320
You land on it, it'll say,
"Expanded, collapsed."

00:28:44.320 --> 00:28:45.360
One of those two options.

00:28:46.160 --> 00:28:49.840
Okay, I get immediate
feedback on the area around me,

00:28:49.840 --> 00:28:51.840
even though I'm just
only on one button.

00:28:52.880 --> 00:28:57.440
When you actually press it, you
get immediate feedback because

00:28:57.440 --> 00:29:00.640
here's the trick
about buttons and,

00:29:01.600 --> 00:29:04.160
yeah, generally
buttons for screen readers,

00:29:04.160 --> 00:29:10.240
is that, as a sighted user,
if you pressed on a link and

00:29:10.240 --> 00:29:13.280
nothing happened, how
long would you wait?

00:29:14.480 --> 00:29:16.960
How long before you
go, "Did it work?

00:29:18.880 --> 00:29:19.440
Is it thinking?

00:29:20.400 --> 00:29:21.200
Is there something wrong?"

00:29:22.560 --> 00:29:24.800
That's pretty much what you
actually have to deal with as a

00:29:24.800 --> 00:29:27.760
screen reader user on every
single button because you press

00:29:27.760 --> 00:29:31.280
it and nothing's announced so
if you don't use aria live,

00:29:31.280 --> 00:29:32.480
if you don't do
focus management,

00:29:32.480 --> 00:29:34.320
if you don't do these
attributes like aria-expanded,

00:29:35.120 --> 00:29:36.320
how long do I wait?

00:29:36.320 --> 00:29:37.760
Did it work?
I don't know.

00:29:39.040 --> 00:29:42.880
So aria-expanded gives that
opportunity to immediately say,

00:29:42.880 --> 00:29:45.040
"Expanded," and
let users know, "Oh,

00:29:45.040 --> 00:29:47.440
okay, this worked and I
can continue along

00:29:47.440 --> 00:29:48.240
in my traversal."

00:29:50.240 --> 00:29:51.040
Aria labels.

00:29:52.320 --> 00:29:54.720
Aria labels are great and
in the presentation so far,

00:29:54.720 --> 00:29:56.000
there's even been
references to them,

00:29:56.000 --> 00:29:56.640
how to do it.

00:29:57.520 --> 00:29:59.120
Just understand it's
a double-edged sword.

00:30:00.800 --> 00:30:04.000
If you overwrite all
of your links with,

00:30:04.000 --> 00:30:05.840
let's say, "Oh, I'm
gonna benefit people,

00:30:05.840 --> 00:30:08.720
and I'm gonna say, 'Open to a
new window,' on every single

00:30:08.720 --> 00:30:11.200
link and I'm gonna do it
as an aria label," well,

00:30:11.200 --> 00:30:12.880
the danger of aria
label is that it actually,

00:30:14.960 --> 00:30:16.880
all of its children
inside that anchor,

00:30:16.880 --> 00:30:19.600
inside that button, are
actually removed and not really

00:30:19.600 --> 00:30:20.720
accessible anymore.

00:30:20.720 --> 00:30:23.360
And only the label itself is
going to be announced to screen

00:30:23.360 --> 00:30:24.320
reader users.

00:30:24.320 --> 00:30:26.960
So you pretty much
negated any visual text,

00:30:28.480 --> 00:30:32.480
any information, and only
supplied what's in that label.

00:30:32.480 --> 00:30:35.520
So if all you had was "Opens in
a new window," you've just ended

00:30:35.520 --> 00:30:37.360
up in a site with a whole
bunch of links that just say,

00:30:37.360 --> 00:30:39.040
"Open in a new window."
Just not helpful.

00:30:39.760 --> 00:30:42.800
So you have to front load and
actually include all of that

00:30:42.800 --> 00:30:44.800
visual text for
it to make sense.

00:30:46.240 --> 00:30:48.320
This also impacts
voice dictation users so,

00:30:48.320 --> 00:30:51.200
like I talked about
LipSurf, you know.

00:30:51.200 --> 00:30:54.320
Now, the technology's changing,
VoiceOver actually even puts in

00:30:54.320 --> 00:30:55.680
grid-view option
so they can say,

00:30:55.680 --> 00:30:59.680
like, "Tap 10," and a lot of
opportunities to not have to

00:30:59.680 --> 00:31:04.240
rely on the actual phrase of the
button that you're interacting

00:31:04.240 --> 00:31:06.000
with, but there's
plenty that do,

00:31:06.000 --> 00:31:08.400
and so if you overwrite the
accessible name there's a large

00:31:08.400 --> 00:31:11.840
potential for voice users to
not even be able to access

00:31:11.840 --> 00:31:12.480
those buttons.

00:31:14.720 --> 00:31:16.000
Another one, you know,

00:31:16.000 --> 00:31:18.080
is aria-current
equals page, true.

00:31:19.200 --> 00:31:23.600
I kind of point those out so
if we take a look at even W3C,

00:31:24.880 --> 00:31:28.640
to understand the reference, we
always create sighted aspects to

00:31:28.640 --> 00:31:31.600
say, "Okay, there's some visual
indication of what page

00:31:31.600 --> 00:31:33.040
you're on," right?

00:31:33.040 --> 00:31:35.120
In navigation,
sidebars, all these things,

00:31:35.120 --> 00:31:37.760
there's usually some
class equals active,

00:31:37.760 --> 00:31:38.960
and some background color.

00:31:41.520 --> 00:31:43.600
Screen readers just don't
get provided that information.

00:31:44.240 --> 00:31:46.320
There's nothing visual for them.

00:31:47.440 --> 00:31:51.280
So, that's where aria-current
equals page now will announce

00:31:51.280 --> 00:31:52.080
something for them.

00:31:52.080 --> 00:31:54.400
And pagination, maybe sometimes
they're not always going to

00:31:54.400 --> 00:31:57.840
different pages so then you also
have aria-current equals true to

00:31:57.840 --> 00:31:59.520
actually announce kind of, hey,

00:31:59.520 --> 00:32:01.200
this is the current
one of this set.

00:32:03.120 --> 00:32:06.320
And something that I don't think
a lot of devs realize is that

00:32:06.320 --> 00:32:10.880
CSS display properties actually
impact the accessibility and the

00:32:10.880 --> 00:32:14.640
semantics of anything, really.

00:32:14.640 --> 00:32:16.720
I mean, it's kind of,
if you think about it,

00:32:16.720 --> 00:32:19.600
display none makes it so screen
readers and assisted technology

00:32:19.600 --> 00:32:22.080
keyboard users, no
one can access it.

00:32:22.080 --> 00:32:25.920
It's already showing that
display properties impact the

00:32:25.920 --> 00:32:28.400
semantics and the
accessibility of HTML.

00:32:29.440 --> 00:32:34.880
And so, if even, you know,
Adrian also went over a nice

00:32:34.880 --> 00:32:37.360
little explanation and
it's a good example of,

00:32:37.360 --> 00:32:39.520
okay, well,
responsive tables, right?

00:32:39.520 --> 00:32:42.000
So if you do display
block, display flex,

00:32:42.000 --> 00:32:44.720
on a table, that loses
all of its semantic value.

00:32:46.000 --> 00:32:49.040
So these are the common things
that I started to see as I

00:32:49.040 --> 00:32:52.960
analyze sites, look through
sites and it's not exhaustive.

00:32:52.960 --> 00:32:55.840
There's plenty more out there.
There's a lot of new ones here.

00:32:58.880 --> 00:33:00.880
So you kind of
go, "Wait a second.

00:33:01.920 --> 00:33:04.000
He's pretty much spent the whole
entire time saying there's lots

00:33:04.000 --> 00:33:05.680
of problems,
there's lots of issues,

00:33:05.680 --> 00:33:07.760
and it's all on me
and I'm, you know,

00:33:07.760 --> 00:33:09.840
scared and
frightened about all this."

00:33:10.960 --> 00:33:14.000
But I'm actually not that
pessimistic about this.

00:33:14.000 --> 00:33:17.840
I'm actually quite optimistic
'cause when I look at over the

00:33:17.840 --> 00:33:21.840
years that there were plenty
of people announcing--

00:33:22.400 --> 00:33:23.120
making a voice.

00:33:23.120 --> 00:33:26.000
But probably in the past five
years I've only seen a huge

00:33:26.000 --> 00:33:27.200
increase in the
number of voices,

00:33:27.200 --> 00:33:29.360
the number of devs,
the number of companies,

00:33:29.360 --> 00:33:33.680
that are waking up and realizing
the accessibility needs.

00:33:35.040 --> 00:33:37.840
There's--if any time to
jump into accessibility,

00:33:38.400 --> 00:33:39.280
now's a great time.

00:33:40.480 --> 00:33:43.280
And so that's why I kind of say,
the future still looks--

00:33:43.280 --> 00:33:44.960
it's very promising.

00:33:44.960 --> 00:33:48.560
We have so many
voices out there,

00:33:49.280 --> 00:33:50.320
so many opportunities.

00:33:50.960 --> 00:33:54.000
Joe Dolson and the team
putting together information.

00:33:55.520 --> 00:33:57.920
Gutenberg, all of these areas,
are still improving

00:33:59.440 --> 00:34:00.720
and you can as well.

00:34:00.720 --> 00:34:01.840
And you can be part of that.

00:34:01.840 --> 00:34:04.160
So that's why I kind of
say, you know, devs unite.

00:34:04.160 --> 00:34:08.240
Let's work together and
create a better future.

00:34:08.240 --> 00:34:11.440
Let's get out of this, you know,
image of the dark tunnel and

00:34:11.440 --> 00:34:15.280
into the brighter future that
we can help so many people with

00:34:15.280 --> 00:34:19.840
disabilities and
improve life for everyone.

00:34:23.520 --> 00:34:27.520
All right, questions.

00:34:28.120 --> 00:34:31.040
Amanda: All right, thanks
so much, Nick.

00:34:31.040 --> 00:34:34.080
I can really tell
how passionate and,

00:34:34.880 --> 00:34:38.320
you know, how much
this is important to you.

00:34:38.320 --> 00:34:44.000
We do have some questions
from the viewers out here,

00:34:44.560 --> 00:34:49.920
so we have, yeah, we have about
15 minutes for the Q&amp;A session.

00:34:50.960 --> 00:34:56.560
First question was: "Do
you recommend a starter or

00:34:56.560 --> 00:34:57.840
accessibility-ready theme?"

00:34:57.840 --> 00:35:00.240
Nick: All of them
have really good points.

00:35:00.240 --> 00:35:02.640
I don't wanna say, like,
"Oh, this has to be the one."

00:35:02.640 --> 00:35:04.560
It's still just, I
would say, go through them.

00:35:04.560 --> 00:35:06.080
Find ones that
really align with you,

00:35:06.720 --> 00:35:09.360
because they have been
vetted, they have been reviewed.

00:35:09.360 --> 00:35:11.520
Of course, there's always room
for improvement for any of them

00:35:11.520 --> 00:35:14.400
but, you know, the
main pain point is,

00:35:15.040 --> 00:35:17.840
you know, we've worked on many
projects ourselves in WordPress

00:35:17.840 --> 00:35:21.280
and a lot of times there is
that page builder aspect where,

00:35:21.280 --> 00:35:23.120
you know, there's
even Genesis Frameworks,

00:35:23.120 --> 00:35:26.560
aspects like that where
they still don't have the page

00:35:26.560 --> 00:35:28.320
builder that many
clients, at the end of the day,

00:35:28.320 --> 00:35:29.680
wanna say, "I just
wanna drag and drop.

00:35:29.680 --> 00:35:30.720
I just wanna put something in."

00:35:31.680 --> 00:35:34.480
And that's usually where the
pain point starts to come out.

00:35:34.480 --> 00:35:37.760
So if you are just creating more
of a simple site and you can

00:35:37.760 --> 00:35:40.080
just build it off of the
basic WordPress set up,

00:35:41.040 --> 00:35:43.360
any of those accessibility
themes are going to be

00:35:43.360 --> 00:35:45.040
beneficial to you
and I would say,

00:35:45.040 --> 00:35:46.320
"Take a look
through these themes.

00:35:46.320 --> 00:35:47.840
Find one that aligns with
you and that's probably

00:35:47.840 --> 00:35:48.640
a good starting point."

00:35:49.240 --> 00:35:51.520
Amanda: Awesome.
Okay, thank you.

00:35:52.640 --> 00:35:58.320
Next question is: "Why don't
developers lock in required

00:35:58.320 --> 00:36:01.600
accessibility items within
repository themes and plugins?

00:36:02.480 --> 00:36:07.040
For example, requiring all text
on all image or video content

00:36:07.040 --> 00:36:10.000
added or color
contrast, et cetera."

00:36:10.000 --> 00:36:13.120
Nick: So, this is where
it gets tricky 'cause it's a

00:36:13.120 --> 00:36:14.000
two-way street, right?

00:36:14.640 --> 00:36:16.880
It's not just devs, it's also
really site ownership

00:36:16.880 --> 00:36:17.920
so content has all.

00:36:17.920 --> 00:36:20.160
You could say,
"Everything needs an alt text."

00:36:20.160 --> 00:36:22.960
But actually, it's not that
simple because there are times,

00:36:22.960 --> 00:36:24.640
so let's say it's all
inside of an anchor, right?

00:36:24.640 --> 00:36:28.560
So you have images and text and
a whole bunch of information,

00:36:28.560 --> 00:36:30.000
all inside of an anchor tag.

00:36:30.960 --> 00:36:33.120
Well, if the image is--let's say
it's a product, right?

00:36:33.920 --> 00:36:36.800
And you're buying
men's gloves, let's say.

00:36:37.440 --> 00:36:41.840
And men's gloves, the
picture is of men's gloves.

00:36:42.480 --> 00:36:46.480
Maybe you could get into some
poetic way to describe them but,

00:36:46.480 --> 00:36:48.640
to a degree, most
people end up just going,

00:36:49.520 --> 00:36:50.640
"Men's gloves."

00:36:50.640 --> 00:36:53.600
So in that anchor, now
you've got alt text that says,

00:36:53.600 --> 00:36:54.800
"Men's gloves, men's gloves."

00:36:55.680 --> 00:36:59.520
Well, it's men's gloves and then
the title of men's gloves that

00:36:59.520 --> 00:37:00.960
would be inside
that same anchor.

00:37:00.960 --> 00:37:04.400
So in that case, you actually
want to say "alt equals blank,"

00:37:04.400 --> 00:37:05.840
or nul, in a sense.

00:37:05.840 --> 00:37:07.760
And you would actually still
want that attribute but you

00:37:07.760 --> 00:37:09.120
don't actually want
it to be explained.

00:37:11.040 --> 00:37:15.280
Videos enforcing captions for
everything is not that simple

00:37:15.920 --> 00:37:19.200
and a lot of times,
like, let's say Netflix,

00:37:19.200 --> 00:37:23.200
for example, when--having
audio descriptions and captions.

00:37:23.200 --> 00:37:25.200
They went through some
suits themselves and,

00:37:26.240 --> 00:37:27.600
you know, I think
initially they were,

00:37:27.600 --> 00:37:30.800
like, "Okay, we have audio
descriptions for 2000 videos."

00:37:31.680 --> 00:37:33.280
And you go, "Yeah, great."

00:37:34.320 --> 00:37:36.040
How many videos
does Netflix have?

00:37:36.040 --> 00:37:37.360
Amanda: Brilliant.

00:37:37.360 --> 00:37:42.000
Nick: So, enforcing is
tough because content creators,

00:37:42.000 --> 00:37:44.800
would you wanna say you
can't launch because

00:37:45.520 --> 00:37:46.560
you don't have it done yet?

00:37:47.600 --> 00:37:50.640
Okay, well, how
long will it take?

00:37:52.640 --> 00:37:54.800
Now, it should be built in,
it should be best practices,

00:37:54.800 --> 00:37:56.240
but it's hard to enforce that.

00:37:56.240 --> 00:37:57.760
'Cause it's really
on the content side.

00:37:58.560 --> 00:37:59.680
And there's sometimes no answer.

00:37:59.680 --> 00:38:03.840
So devs, still it would be great
to enforce but it still probably

00:38:03.840 --> 00:38:08.560
would be, you know, you have to
flag to say it's allowed because

00:38:08.560 --> 00:38:11.920
even the WCAG spec says if
this is gonna prevent a launch,

00:38:11.920 --> 00:38:15.040
that you don't have one
video with closed captions,

00:38:17.680 --> 00:38:19.200
that's not a reason to stop.

00:38:19.200 --> 00:38:21.520
It's about a due diligence
plan, and working towards it.

00:38:22.640 --> 00:38:24.000
Now, I request it.

00:38:24.000 --> 00:38:26.400
Yes, it would be great to
make sure everything has that.

00:38:27.360 --> 00:38:32.480
But we also have to be realists
and I know that's not great but

00:38:32.480 --> 00:38:34.720
if you think about buildings,
accessibility of a building,

00:38:35.280 --> 00:38:38.160
how often does it get
renovated versus a website.

00:38:39.120 --> 00:38:40.720
When's the last time
you updated a page?

00:38:40.720 --> 00:38:46.160
Probably maybe even
since 8 a.m. today.

00:38:46.160 --> 00:38:47.120
Hopefully, that helps answer.

00:38:47.120 --> 00:38:50.400
Amanda: Yeah, no, I think
that was a great answer and a

00:38:50.400 --> 00:38:52.000
really great
question, so thank you.

00:38:53.600 --> 00:38:54.400
Let's see.

00:38:54.400 --> 00:38:55.760
If there are
additional questions,

00:38:55.760 --> 00:38:58.000
you can continue to
put them in the chat.

00:38:58.800 --> 00:39:02.960
The next question for Nick
is: "Can you suggest automated

00:39:02.960 --> 00:39:07.440
workflow tools for preflight
accessibility checks and are

00:39:07.440 --> 00:39:09.480
there any that you
would recommend?"

00:39:09.480 --> 00:39:13.280
Nick: Okay, so you wanna
kind of have build tools to kind

00:39:13.280 --> 00:39:16.640
of run through and run against
it so that you could actually

00:39:16.640 --> 00:39:20.320
catch these issues before you
actually even go live or go up

00:39:20.320 --> 00:39:21.760
into a production environment.

00:39:22.560 --> 00:39:23.760
And there's a lot out there--

00:39:23.760 --> 00:39:27.040
aXe and these other tools,
you can actually build it in.

00:39:28.080 --> 00:39:29.520
There's a lot out there.

00:39:29.520 --> 00:39:32.000
It's--they'll have--the
main thing I would say,

00:39:32.800 --> 00:39:35.840
you know, I mentioned Pa11y as
well if you wanted to kind of

00:39:35.840 --> 00:39:37.360
create dashboards
and run through it

00:39:37.360 --> 00:39:38.400
and run 'em against builds.

00:39:40.480 --> 00:39:43.840
Again, it'll only help you catch
so much so the main thing I

00:39:43.840 --> 00:39:47.840
would stress is that it'll help
you a little bit but there's

00:39:47.840 --> 00:39:51.040
always gonna be false positives,
there's going to be aspects that

00:39:51.040 --> 00:39:51.920
are going to be missed,

00:39:52.560 --> 00:39:54.560
so it at least steps you in the
right direction.

00:39:56.240 --> 00:39:58.320
But it doesn't actually
really solve everything.

00:39:58.320 --> 00:40:01.440
So that's where it's really
important you look at your own

00:40:01.440 --> 00:40:03.920
code, review it,
and make sure you,

00:40:03.920 --> 00:40:05.680
you know, just even run
through it with a keyboard.

00:40:05.680 --> 00:40:07.200
Run through it
with a screen reader.

00:40:07.200 --> 00:40:08.240
Run through it
with these things,

00:40:09.040 --> 00:40:13.920
and help catch it before it
even--it bypasses a build tool

00:40:13.920 --> 00:40:16.640
to then go to a live site.

00:40:18.120 --> 00:40:20.400
Amanda: Okay,
great, I think, yes,

00:40:20.400 --> 00:40:22.400
diligence is key,
testing is key,

00:40:22.400 --> 00:40:23.840
as you mentioned.

00:40:24.800 --> 00:40:27.120
Okay, so we've got two
more questions here.

00:40:27.120 --> 00:40:30.960
The next one is: "How would
you rank the page builders in

00:40:30.960 --> 00:40:33.360
relation to accessibility?

00:40:33.360 --> 00:40:36.400
Page builders always seem to be
adding new features but is one

00:40:36.400 --> 00:40:38.880
working faster or more
diligently to make their product

00:40:38.880 --> 00:40:39.920
better in this area?"

00:40:41.280 --> 00:40:46.880
Nick: Yeah, I
would say, you know,

00:40:46.880 --> 00:40:48.720
we've switched
through a couple ourselves.

00:40:51.440 --> 00:40:55.120
Again, Beaver Builder still
had some issues and we kind of

00:40:55.120 --> 00:40:57.680
switched over and we've been
working a bit with Elementor.

00:40:59.200 --> 00:41:01.760
But we still have to hack
around it, to be honest.

00:41:01.760 --> 00:41:04.400
It's really--if you know
a system and you know the

00:41:04.400 --> 00:41:08.320
structure and you know the tools
that are available, at the end

00:41:08.320 --> 00:41:09.600
of the day it kind
of comes down to,

00:41:09.600 --> 00:41:11.520
okay, well, if you're
getting used to those,

00:41:11.520 --> 00:41:14.640
it's about making sure you have
the javascript workarounds or

00:41:14.640 --> 00:41:18.960
the PHP workarounds or the
customizations to fix it.

00:41:18.960 --> 00:41:22.560
So that's why I kind of say it's
a lot of patchwork and a lot of

00:41:22.560 --> 00:41:28.720
fixing potholes and it's hard
to say 'cause I see times where

00:41:28.720 --> 00:41:30.880
they make improvements
and then they regress.

00:41:32.080 --> 00:41:36.560
I see, you know, advocacy and
then I see things sitting for a

00:41:36.560 --> 00:41:37.200
couple of years.

00:41:38.160 --> 00:41:40.720
Because it--all the
people making it, right?

00:41:41.360 --> 00:41:43.360
How many people are involved?
How much time does it take?

00:41:43.360 --> 00:41:45.600
I mean, if you look at it,
Gutenberg ran

00:41:45.600 --> 00:41:47.040
into the same situation, right?

00:41:47.600 --> 00:41:50.560
They had to now go back through
and start to fix and resolve

00:41:50.560 --> 00:41:53.360
items, and there are still gonna
be issues that come up

00:41:53.360 --> 00:41:54.320
once in a while.

00:41:54.320 --> 00:41:56.000
It's never one and
done, unfortunately.

00:41:57.200 --> 00:41:59.440
So I don't wanna
be, "Oh, absolutely,

00:41:59.440 --> 00:42:02.720
this one," because I haven't
vetted every single one of them

00:42:02.720 --> 00:42:05.280
'cause that'd be a lot of
time on myself as well.

00:42:05.280 --> 00:42:07.920
So there could be, actually, a
really good one that caters to

00:42:07.920 --> 00:42:09.760
you because you know it so well.

00:42:11.080 --> 00:42:12.640
Amanda: Okay, great.

00:42:13.600 --> 00:42:15.440
Okay, we did get another
question so there's

00:42:15.440 --> 00:42:16.320
still two more questions.

00:42:17.680 --> 00:42:20.240
"Where do you feel developers
could make the most positive

00:42:20.240 --> 00:42:23.120
impact on
accessibility," and then,

00:42:23.840 --> 00:42:25.680
in parentheses, it
says, "type of contribute,

00:42:25.680 --> 00:42:28.400
feature area, et cetera."

00:42:28.400 --> 00:42:29.840
Nick: That's a good one.

00:42:33.760 --> 00:42:36.720
Like I said, I
think in one way it is,

00:42:37.840 --> 00:42:39.600
as developers, how
can we contribute?

00:42:39.600 --> 00:42:43.760
The first thing is getting
into another person's shoes,

00:42:43.760 --> 00:42:45.600
is to break
outside of ourselves.

00:42:45.600 --> 00:42:48.560
The more--all developers--if
all developers and all,

00:42:48.560 --> 00:42:50.480
you know, site
owners pretty much said,

00:42:50.480 --> 00:42:53.520
"I'm not gonna just think
about me," a lot of our design

00:42:53.520 --> 00:42:55.840
concepts and a lot of
our development concepts,

00:42:55.840 --> 00:42:58.160
a lot of the
things that we create,

00:42:58.160 --> 00:43:01.200
infinite scroll items, all of
the concepts that we create that

00:43:01.200 --> 00:43:04.160
go, "Wow," probably would have
had some more thought into them

00:43:04.880 --> 00:43:06.080
on the impact that it is.

00:43:06.800 --> 00:43:08.160
So that's why I
kind of say, you know,

00:43:08.160 --> 00:43:09.280
the thing that I
would stress is,

00:43:09.280 --> 00:43:11.360
you know, if you haven't
picked up any of these tools,

00:43:11.360 --> 00:43:13.840
any accessor technology,
dive into it for a day.

00:43:14.560 --> 00:43:18.640
Close your eyes and just try and
even use a normal site that you

00:43:18.640 --> 00:43:20.400
do every single day, and
could you actually

00:43:20.400 --> 00:43:21.280
understand what it is?

00:43:22.640 --> 00:43:24.080
But if you were to
contribute--right?--

00:43:25.920 --> 00:43:29.040
really, if you've gotten really
good at accessibility and you

00:43:29.040 --> 00:43:31.520
know a fair amount and you
wanna be able to contribute,

00:43:31.520 --> 00:43:33.280
be another voice by all means.

00:43:33.280 --> 00:43:35.280
If you've found
something, blog it, post it.

00:43:36.640 --> 00:43:39.680
For these, you know,
open-source tools,

00:43:39.680 --> 00:43:40.480
contribute, right?

00:43:41.200 --> 00:43:43.040
They've got problems and
you've been having to hack

00:43:43.040 --> 00:43:44.560
around it over and
over and over again,

00:43:45.600 --> 00:43:50.320
here's the hack or here's an
approach to do it and try and,

00:43:50.320 --> 00:43:53.840
you know, fork and try and
actually do poll requests.

00:43:55.240 --> 00:43:56.720
Amanda: Okay, great.

00:43:56.720 --> 00:43:59.440
I think that's very much
in the spirit of WordPress

00:43:59.440 --> 00:44:01.040
Accessibility Day,
you know, having

00:44:01.680 --> 00:44:03.680
so many experts together, so.

00:44:03.680 --> 00:44:07.200
And the last question is, I
guess, more of a personal one.

00:44:08.400 --> 00:44:11.280
They said--the comment is, "I
love your approach on testing.

00:44:11.280 --> 00:44:13.920
So what drew you to
accessibility and who has

00:44:13.920 --> 00:44:15.000
influenced you?"

00:44:15.000 --> 00:44:19.040
Nick: Yeah, no, it's
a lot of people have.

00:44:20.000 --> 00:44:23.920
Close family, you know, they
themselves have issues that

00:44:23.920 --> 00:44:24.640
they're dealing with.

00:44:25.600 --> 00:44:30.240
Mine's not as fanciful,
like, but it's really just,

00:44:34.560 --> 00:44:38.400
I think, maybe being abroad,
maybe living abroad teaches you,

00:44:38.400 --> 00:44:42.080
it's just like, again, break
outside of your mold and break

00:44:42.080 --> 00:44:44.720
outside of yourself and
start to empathize with others.

00:44:44.720 --> 00:44:47.360
And so, yeah, did I
make mistakes early on?

00:44:47.360 --> 00:44:49.840
Oh, absolutely, I made
some bad code decisions.

00:44:49.840 --> 00:44:51.120
I thought, "Oh, this is cool."

00:44:52.000 --> 00:44:53.840
But when I started to
realize the impact,

00:44:54.720 --> 00:44:56.560
it really started to
get to me, kind of go,

00:44:56.560 --> 00:44:59.840
like, "Well, a lot of these
principles are just basics.

00:44:59.840 --> 00:45:01.200
We've lost sight of the basics.

00:45:01.760 --> 00:45:04.080
You know, accessibility
principles for the web have been

00:45:04.080 --> 00:45:07.680
around for 20-plus years and
somewhere along the line we

00:45:07.680 --> 00:45:09.200
wanted to get cooler
and cooler and cooler,

00:45:09.760 --> 00:45:11.520
and it's not that
you can't be cool.

00:45:11.520 --> 00:45:13.840
You can create really
interesting interfaces,

00:45:14.560 --> 00:45:16.640
but you just have to
remember the basics.

00:45:17.200 --> 00:45:18.960
The amount of times
that I don't see a button,

00:45:18.960 --> 00:45:21.040
you know, again, all
these job script frameworks,

00:45:21.760 --> 00:45:24.000
it's not that the job script
framework is bad as a whole,

00:45:24.000 --> 00:45:25.600
you know, React,
Angular, all of them.

00:45:25.600 --> 00:45:29.200
It's that the people doing
it don't remember the basics.

00:45:30.960 --> 00:45:34.000
And so, I guess that just deeply
influenced me where it was like,

00:45:34.000 --> 00:45:35.840
"Oh, I can actually
make a difference."

00:45:36.480 --> 00:45:38.080
And then, the benefits, right?

00:45:38.080 --> 00:45:40.880
The--plenty of presenters
so far have gone over SEO,

00:45:41.760 --> 00:45:43.600
user experience as a whole.

00:45:43.600 --> 00:45:44.880
There's a lot of alignment.

00:45:45.760 --> 00:45:48.240
So when I first started
on, really diving in,

00:45:48.240 --> 00:45:49.680
I started, you know,
people would always ask,

00:45:49.680 --> 00:45:51.280
it's like, you know,
devil's advocate:

00:45:52.560 --> 00:45:54.080
"Why focus on accessibility?"

00:45:54.080 --> 00:45:56.000
And I can hear people
presenting and they're,

00:45:56.000 --> 00:45:58.160
like, "I--'cause you should."

00:45:59.840 --> 00:46:04.640
Like, yeah, but I think, you
know, that's not always

00:46:04.640 --> 00:46:05.280
so realistic.

00:46:06.320 --> 00:46:08.000
It's kind of sad
in some ways that,

00:46:08.000 --> 00:46:10.000
you know, you would think
it should be that easy.

00:46:11.280 --> 00:46:13.040
So it got me really
passionate and kind of going,

00:46:13.040 --> 00:46:15.920
like, "How can I express this
to people so organizations,

00:46:15.920 --> 00:46:18.320
clients, can finally
realize the benefits?"

00:46:19.280 --> 00:46:21.600
And so, generally, if you
need to express something,

00:46:21.600 --> 00:46:24.240
you know, get buy-in within
your companies or a client or

00:46:24.240 --> 00:46:27.040
something, is I always go
with the selfish method.

00:46:27.920 --> 00:46:30.560
You know, it's if you
just scare them with legal,

00:46:31.280 --> 00:46:34.560
they'll do just enough
ounces of flair

00:46:34.560 --> 00:46:37.040
to get along, get by.

00:46:38.240 --> 00:46:41.840
It's, "Hey, did you know that
you'd get benefits of SEO," and

00:46:41.840 --> 00:46:43.920
they'd be, like,
"Ooh, ooh, ooh, SEO,

00:46:43.920 --> 00:46:44.960
that's much more important."

00:46:45.840 --> 00:46:47.280
If you kind of
point out, you know,

00:46:47.280 --> 00:46:50.560
"Oh, okay, well, you know,
the amount of people with

00:46:50.560 --> 00:46:52.640
disabilities that you
could increase," right?

00:46:52.640 --> 00:46:53.760
An e-comm site.

00:46:53.760 --> 00:46:55.840
"You could increase up to
20% the amount of users."

00:46:56.960 --> 00:47:00.960
Banks, "Hey, stop
thinking of it as--you know,

00:47:00.960 --> 00:47:02.720
you always talk about
wanting to be individuals,

00:47:02.720 --> 00:47:06.240
wanting to be, you
know, about the people.

00:47:06.240 --> 00:47:09.520
Well, you can create marketing
campaigns about how you're about

00:47:09.520 --> 00:47:10.960
the people and you've
worked hard

00:47:10.960 --> 00:47:12.400
to make the accessibility."

00:47:12.400 --> 00:47:15.440
So that usually then gets the
buy-in to then finally do the

00:47:15.440 --> 00:47:16.640
thing that I
wanted to do all along,

00:47:16.640 --> 00:47:19.120
which is make sure the
sites are accessible.

00:47:20.840 --> 00:47:22.880
Amanda: All right, perfect.

00:47:22.880 --> 00:47:26.320
Thank you so much, and for
everyone that asked questions,

00:47:26.320 --> 00:47:27.840
thank you, those
were great questions.

00:47:29.520 --> 00:47:31.520
Nick, it's been a
pleasure having you and,

00:47:32.800 --> 00:47:35.520
again, thanks, everyone,
for attending this session,

00:47:35.520 --> 00:47:38.960
"Developers Unite: Navigating
Accessibility in WordPress."

00:47:38.960 --> 00:47:39.084
...

